04159nam a22006615i 9781575066448DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750664487 a10.1515/97815750664482doi  a(DE-B1597)584344  a(OCoLC)1266229068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBS1225.52.R67 2011eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a221.10661 aRoskop, Angela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wilderness Itineraries :bGenre, Geography, and the Growth of Torah /cAngela Roskop. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory, Archaeology, and Culture of the Levant ;v30 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs we read the wilderness narrative, we are confronted with a wide variety of cues that shape our sense of what kind of narrative it is, often in conflicting ways. It often appears to be history, but it also contains genres and content that are not historiographical. To explain this unique blend, Roskop charts a path through Akkadian and Egyptian administrative and historiographical texts, exploring the way the itinerary genre was used in innovative ways as scribes served new literary goals that arose in different historical and social situations. She marries literary theory with philology and archaeology to show that the wilderness narrative came about as Israelite scribes used both the itinerary genre and geography in profoundly creative ways, creating a narrative repository for pieces of Israelite history and culture so that they might not be forgotten but continue to shape communal life under new circumstances.The itinerary notices also play an important role in the growth of the Torah. Many scholars have expressed frustration with historical criticism because it seems at times to focus more on deconstructing a narrative than explaining how this composite text manages to work as a whole. The Wilderness Itineraries explores the way that fractures in the itinerary chain and geographical problems serve both as clues to the composition history of the wilderness narrative and as cues for ways to navigate these fractures and read this composite text as a unified whole. Readers will gain insight into the technical skill and creativity of ancient Israelite scribes as they engaged in the process of simultaneously preserving and actively shaping the Torah as a work of historiography without parallel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChronology, Historical. 0aTravel in the Bible. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575066448?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575066448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781575066448/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK